      Naked short selling
   =20
 =20

=E2=80=9CNaked short selling is an imaginary problem,=E2=80=9D   I said las=
t week, enraging apparently hundreds of very online investors in a now-priv=
ate oil company called Next Bridge Hydrocarbons Inc. for reasons that are, =
I promise, not worth getting into. And so of course yesterday the US Securi=
ties and Exchange Commission  brought a naked short selling enforcement act=
ion:

The Securities and Exchange Commission today charged investment adviser Sab=
by Management LLC and its managing partner, Hal D. Mintz, with fraud in con=
nection with a long running scheme involving misrepresentations and violati=
ons of rules for short selling and order making, as well as other violative=
 trading, that generated more than $2 million in illegal profits.
The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint alleges that, from at least March 2017 through =
May 2019, Sabby and Mintz repeatedly circumvented trading rules to conduct =
unlawful trades in the stock of at least 10 public companies. Short selling=
 is a legal practice where, generally, a trader borrows a security from a s=
ecurityholder and sells the security at one price, speculating that the tra=
der can buy the security at a lower price in the future before it must be r=
eturned to its owner. As alleged in the complaint, for example, Sabby and M=
intz engaged in illegal =E2=80=9Cnaked short selling=E2=80=9D by intentiona=
lly and improperly placing short sales when they knew or were reckless in n=
ot knowing that they had not borrowed or located the shares, and then faile=
d to make timely delivery of the shares. According to the SEC=E2=80=99s com=
plaint, the purpose of Sabby and Mintz=E2=80=99s fraudulent scheme was to e=
arn profits they could not have gained through legal trading.

The  basic rule is that if you want to sell stock short =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=
 is, sell it without owning it, to bet on its decline =E2=80=94=C2=A0you ha=
ve to borrow the stock that you sell from someone who owns it, and generall=
y pay them a fee for the use of their stock.
  [1]
=C2=A0And before you sell the stock,=C2=A0you need to get a =E2=80=9Clocate=
,=E2=80=9D meaning that your broker checks and tells you=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyeah=
 you can probably borrow enough=C2=A0shares for this short.=E2=80=9D
  [2]
=C2=A0You get a locate, you sell the stock, and then you have to deliver th=
e stock when the trade settles two days later. So, between the trade and th=
e settlement,=C2=A0the broker who gave you the locate goes out and actually=
 borrows the stock for you. If you do not borrow the stock in time to settl=
e the transaction, that is called a =E2=80=9Cfail.=E2=80=9D
If you do not get a locate before the trade, or if you do not manage to bor=
row the stock before the trade is supposed to settle (and the trade fails),=
 that is what is sometimes called a =E2=80=9Cnaked short.=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=
=9CIn a =E2=80=98naked=E2=80=99 short sale, a seller does not borrow or arr=
ange to borrow securitiesin time to make delivery to the buyer within the s=
tandard settlement period,=E2=80=9D  says yesterday=E2=80=99s SEC complaint=
.) Naked short selling is somewhere between unfortunate (if, say, a market =
maker does a short sale and can=E2=80=99t find borrow in time for normal se=
ttlement) and illegal (if a hedge fund=C2=A0shorts a=C2=A0stock without bot=
hering to get a locate).
There is out there a conspiracy-theory version of naked short selling.=C2=
=A0In this version, shadowy hedge funds sell millions of shares of stock of=
 some good innocent company, without actually borrowing the stock, and then=
 keep these short positions open forever, driving the company=E2=80=99s sto=
ck down to profit from its failure. This version does not make a ton of sen=
se. For one thing, brokers won=E2=80=99t actually let you keep naked short =
positions open forever: If you can=E2=80=99t borrow the stock reasonably pr=
omptly, they=E2=80=99ll  close out your position by buying back the stock.
Also many of the conspiracy-theory versions involve confusion between=C2=A0=
naked=C2=A0short selling and just=C2=A0regular=C2=A0short selling. Conspira=
cy theorists sometimes point out that people often   own more than 100% of =
the outstanding shares of some company, which they take to be proof that th=
ere are =E2=80=9Cphantom shares=E2=80=9D created by naked short selling. Bu=
t any=C2=A0short selling =E2=80=94=C2=A0including perfectly legal, clothed =
short selling =E2=80=94=C2=A0will have this effect. If there are 100 shares=
 of a company=E2=80=99s stock outstanding, and Amy owns all of them, and sh=
e=C2=A0lends Ben 20 shares to short, and Ben sells those shares to Camille,=
 then Amy owns 100 shares and Camille owns 20, for a total of 120 shares; t=
here is simply nothing nefarious or unusual about this. (Sadly we have   di=
scussed this a lot.)
More generally, if you just want to bet that a company=E2=80=99s stock will=
 go down, or even=C2=A0drive=C2=A0down the stock with your own selling acti=
vity, you don=E2=80=99t generally need to=C2=A0naked=C2=A0short. Just regul=
ar, legal shorting =E2=80=94=C2=A0borrowing stock and selling it =E2=80=94 =
is a bet against the stock, and if you do enough of it it might move the st=
ock. Naked short selling, as a nefarious plot by hedge funds to drive good =
companies out of business, still seems to me to be a largely imaginary prob=
lem.
There is, however, a good=C2=A0(illegal! but possibly lucrative)=C2=A0real =
use case for naked shorting, albeit sort of a strange and specialized one. =
It goes like this:
=09A publicly traded company is having some tough times and is looking to r=
aise a bit of money. Ordinary financing options like a bond deal or a publi=
c stock offering are not available for whatever reason, so the company is l=
ooking for weird trades.=09You arrange=C2=A0to=C2=A0buy some stock from the=
=C2=A0company, in the future, either at a fixed price or at some floating p=
rice indexed to the market price. So you sign a contract to buy 1 million s=
hares two weeks from now at $1 per share (a fixed price), or to buy 1 milli=
on shares two weeks from now at the volume-weighted average price
  [3]
=C2=A0of the stock over next two weeks (a floating price). You are giving t=
he company money, and you are getting back stock, and because the company i=
s a bit desperate you get a pretty good deal.=09The stock is trading at, li=
ke, $1.25 today: You are getting a discount, buying at $1, because the comp=
any needs the money. (Or if you are buying at a floating price, it might be=
 at a discount to the average market price.)=09If you could sell 1 million =
shares at $1.25 today, then in two weeks you will buy them at $1, and you w=
ill make a $250,000 guaranteed profit. Whereas if you wait the two weeks, b=
uy the shares at $1, and=C2=A0then=C2=A0sell them, maybe the stock will be =
below $1 by then and you will lose money. This company is risky! You want t=
o lock in the profit now. (Similarly, but slightly more complicated, with a=
 floating price: You want to sell the stock over the two-week period so you=
 can get=C2=A0the average price, rather than waiting to buy=C2=A0at that pr=
ice and then sell at whatever the price is in two weeks.)=09But, look:=C2=
=A0If you have this sort of arrangement with this sort of troubled company,=
 there is a good chance that=C2=A0it is=C2=A0hard to borrow=C2=A01 million =
shares. The company is small, its stock doesn=E2=80=99t trade that much, pr=
obably a lot of people have already borrowed it to short it.=C2=A0So you ha=
ve to pay a large borrow fee, or more likely you simply cannot find 1 milli=
on shares to borrow at any price.=09If you just=C2=A0naked=C2=A0shorted the=
 stock, and sort of strung your brokers along for two weeks, you=E2=80=99d =
be fine: Sell at $1.25 today, buy at $1 in two weeks, and deliver the 1 mil=
lion shares you=C2=A0bought=C2=A0to close out your short position. No harm =
done!

This is illegal in part because you are unfairly ducking the costs of short=
 selling, but also because it is kind of a scammy way to do a stock=C2=A0of=
fering: You are basically able to lock in a big profit by selling the stock=
 to the company=E2=80=99s public shareholders before you buy it from the co=
mpany, and it seems a bit unfair.
  [4]

We have talked about this idea a few times before.=C2=A0We have   talked, f=
or   instance, about the PIPE (private investment in public equity) deal do=
ne by Digital World Acquisition Corp., the special purpose acquisition comp=
any that is waiting around to try to take Donald Trump=E2=80=99s media comp=
any public. Roughly speaking, the deal there was that the PIPE investors ag=
reed, in December 2021, to buy DWAC stock at $33.60 per share whenever the =
Trump merger closed.
  [5]
=C2=A0The stock was trading at about $45 at the time. The merger still has =
not closed and probably never will; the stock closed yesterday at $12.79. I=
f you had=C2=A0shorted=C2=A0the stock when you signed the PIPE deal, you=E2=
=80=99d be hedged: You sell at $45, the deal closes and you buy back at $33=
.60, or else the deal does not close, the stock falls,=C2=A0and you buy bac=
k at, you know, $10. The PIPE deal=C2=A0specifically allowed investors to s=
hort=C2=A0to lock in this profit. But, I wrote:
There are risks to this trade. One risk is that it might be expensive to bo=
rrow DWAC stock, it=E2=80=99s a meme stock, the price could go up, borrow c=
ould be recalled, and you could be forced to cover your short at a loss bef=
ore the merger closes. If you make it to closing, you=E2=80=99re guaranteed=
 to be able to buy the stock for $33.60 for a risk-free profit, but you had=
 better be sure that your stock borrow is locked up until then. And closing=
 =E2=80=94 which requires writing a public disclosure document that satisfi=
es SEC rules =E2=80=94 could be a long way away.
If somehow you could be naked=C2=A0short for, like, a year and a half or so=
, those problems would be solved and it would be free money. I don=E2=80=99=
t think you could =E2=80=94=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t think anyone did this trad=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you can see how naked shorting would be attractive her=
e.
  [6]

Anyway that=E2=80=99s the sort of trade that Sabby allegedly did, though on=
 a smaller scale and not in DWAC. (Though Sabby=C2=A0is=C2=A0an investor in=
 the DWAC PIPE.)=C2=A0From  yesterday=E2=80=99s SEC complaint:

In April 2018, Defendants, on behalf of the Warrant Fund, entered into a se=
curities purchase agreement with Issuer 1 through which Defendants acquired=
 preferred securities that could be converted into Issuer 1=E2=80=99s commo=
n stock at a conversion price of $0.46 per share. The agreement contained a=
 provision that, on June 25, 2018, the conversion price of the preferred se=
curities would be adjusted to 80% of the volume-weighted average price (=E2=
=80=9CVWAP=E2=80=9D) of Issuer 1=E2=80=99s common stock on the preceding tr=
ading day, June 22, 2018 (=E2=80=9Cthe reset provision=E2=80=9D).
The reset provision gave Defendants a financial incentive to push down the =
price of Issuer 1=E2=80=99s common stock before June 22, 2018 in order to r=
eceive more common stock upon conversion. =E2=80=A6
With two trading days remaining before the reset provision took effect, Def=
endants intentionally began naked short selling Issuer 1=E2=80=99s common s=
tock, putting downward pressure on Issuer 1=E2=80=99s stock price. ...
Throughout the day, Defendants, on behalf of the Warrant Fund, submitted to=
 executing brokerdealers materially false and misleading order instructions=
 for the long sale of 1,126,033 shares=C2=A0of Issuer 1=E2=80=99s common st=
ock that executed at prices between approximately $0.29 and $0.33 per share=
.
Defendants knew, or were reckless in not knowing, that the sale of all but =
286 shares should have been marked as short sales because the Warrant Fund =
did not have a sufficient net long position in the common stock of Issuer 1=
 at the time Defendants submitted the orders.

Basically they did not get a locate for these short sales, and they tricked=
 their brokers into allowing them by marking the sales as =E2=80=9Clong=E2=
=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9Cshort.=E2=80=9D (A =E2=80=9Clong sale=E2=80=9D =
is selling stock that you own; a =E2=80=9Cshort sale=E2=80=9D is selling st=
ock that you borrow. Later they sold more shares marked as short, but =E2=
=80=9Cfalsely represented to the executing broker-dealers that Defendants h=
ad obtained locates.=E2=80=9D) This was, in a legal sense, wrong: They did =
not own the shares they were selling, so these were not long sales. But it =
was in some broad economic sense right: They owned=C2=A0convertible preferr=
ed=C2=A0shares that they could convert into the shares they were selling; t=
hey had economic exposure to the underlying shares, and could get them easi=
ly. And they did:

After the close of trading markets on June 22, 2018, Defendants calculated =
the adjusted conversion rate for the Warrant Fund=E2=80=99s Issuer 1 prefer=
red securities =E2=80=93 based on 80% of VWAP on June 22, 2018 =E2=80=93 to=
 be $0.1779 per share, down from the original rate of $0.46 per share.
At or around 5:31 PM Eastern Time on June 22, 2018, Defendants, on behalf o=
f the Warrant Fund, submitted a conversion notice to Issuer 1 to convert $1=
,797,017 worth of preferred securities into 10,101,280 shares of Issuer 1 c=
ommon stock at a conversion rate of $0.1779 per share.

And so they had enough shares to settle their short sales, which they did, =
on the normal timeline (with no fails).=C2=A0But the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t li=
ke it:
Defendants intended to use these shares to satisfy the delivery obligations=
 for their June 21 and 22, 2018 sales of Issuer 1 common stock and to try t=
o conceal their violative short sales for which they had failed to obtain l=
ocates. However, as Defendants knew or were reckless in not knowing all alo=
ng, the use of these converted shares to cover their sales would not and di=
d not in any way cure their violative trading. Delivery of those shares did=
 not cure the fact that they had mismarked their trades as long sales when =
they were not =E2=80=9Cdeemed to own=E2=80=9D the shares or did not have a =
net long position in Issuer 1 at the time they submitted the mismarked orde=
rs. Similarly, delivery of those shares did not cure their violations of th=
e locate requirements of Regulation SHO because they had placed short sales=
 without actually having obtained a locate, and as Defendants knew or were =
reckless in not knowing, they could not use the fact that they held convert=
ible securities that could be exchanged for Issuer 1 stock to satisfy the l=
ocate requirement.
And they did this because it was lucrative:
If Defendants had converted $1,797,017 worth of Issuer 1 preferred securiti=
es prior to the adjustment of the conversion rate, effective June 25, 2018,=
 the conversion would have yielded only 3,906,560 shares of Issuer 1 common=
 stock. Instead, by tendering the convertible securities after Issuer 1=E2=
=80=99s stock price plummeted by over 60% and the conversion rate was adjus=
ted downward, Sabby=E2=80=99s conversion of $1,797,017 worth of preferred s=
ecurities at the price of $0.1779 per share resulted in approximately 10.1 =
million shares of common stock.
If they had converted at $0.46 and then sold at about $0.19=C2=A0per share =
(the closing price on June 22), they would have lost money. (Also, if they =
converted first and=C2=A0then=C2=A0sold, they would have been entirely at r=
isk =E2=80=94=C2=A0the price could have fallen more.=C2=A0Instead they sold=
 at about $0.22 per share first and then=C2=A0converted at about $0.18 per =
share, a much better trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0both more profitable=C2=A0and=C2=
=A0less risky =E2=80=94=C2=A0though an illegal one.
The SEC goes through another example in which Sabby allegedly (naked) short=
ed a bunch of another company=E2=80=99s stock at prices above $1 and=C2=A0t=
hen=C2=A0signed a purchase agreement with the company to buy 1 million shar=
es at $1, locking in a profit. That is a risky trade, unless you are pretty=
 sure you=E2=80=99re going to be able to buy the stock from the company.
  [7]
 But if you are, it=E2=80=99s a pretty safe trade: If the stock is at $2, a=
nd you sell 1 million shares and push down the price to $1.50, then (1) you=
 probably sold at an average price of about $1.75=C2=A0and (2) you can go t=
o the company and say =E2=80=9Chey, the stock closed at $1.50, but we need =
a discount to the last closing price to make this big purchase, what about =
$1?=E2=80=9D and they=E2=80=99ll probably say yes and you=E2=80=99ll have l=
ocked in a profit of $0.75 per share.
So! I mean: Yes, there is naked short selling, in the world. But notice tha=
t what is happening here is not a shadowy cabal of hedge funds conspiring t=
o push down the prices of companies=E2=80=99 stocks to ruin them, and heroi=
c companies fighting back to save their shareholders from the scourge of na=
ked short selling. What is happening here is a hedge fund working=C2=A0with=
 the companies=C2=A0to give them financing, and (allegedly) using naked sho=
rt selling to make a risk-free profit on the trade at the expense of the co=
mpany=E2=80=99s other, regular shareholders.

