When David Solomon became chief executive officer of Goldman Sachs Group In=
c. in 2018, Goldman did a public-relations push making the following points=
:
=09Solomon moonlights as an electronic dance music DJ.=09Isn=E2=80=99t that=
 cute?=09Nobody thought that someone who DJs could become the CEO of Goldma=
n Sachs. Conservative older bankers regularly advised Solomon to hang up hi=
s headphones, buckle down and take up golf. But he persevered and followed =
his passion and proved the doubters wrong and, in fact, became the CEO of G=
oldman Sachs and also a DJ.

I confess that I did not really believe the last point at all, and I=C2=A0h=
ave over the years made a lot of jokes about this. (Disclosure, I used to w=
ork at Goldman.) People in finance have all sorts of=C2=A0hobbies, and bein=
g what Rusty Foster once called a =E2=80=9Cprofessional amateur DJ=E2=80=9D=
 never struck me as all that weird or challenging. Everyone wants to be the=
 underdog, to tell a story of triumphing over adversity, and if your advers=
ity is being an ambitious investment banker who also DJs then that is fine =
but I am going to make fun of it.
In recent months, though, I have begun to think that I was wrong, and that =
the anonymous conservative older bankers who doubted Solomon might (1) exis=
t and (2) have been right that in fact no one man can successfully be both =
the CEO of Goldman Sachs and also a DJ. In February we discussed=C2=A0a New=
 York Times story about, I swear this headline is real, =E2=80=9CThe Blurre=
d Lines Between Goldman C.E.O.=E2=80=99s Day Job and His D.J. Gig.=E2=80=9D=
 Apparently it is possible to have conflicts of interest between running Go=
ldman Sachs and DJing, and Solomon might have found some, and others at Gol=
dman have griped about them.=C2=A0
And today=E2=80=99s Wall Street Journal has a story with the headline =E2=
=80=9CGoldman Sachs Is at War With Itself=E2=80=9D that begins with this st=
ory:

When Goldman Sachs partners descended on Miami Beach for the bank=E2=80=99s=
 annual confab of senior leaders in February, it was a former CEO, Lloyd Bl=
ankfein, who stole the show.
Blankfein, holding court at the hotel bar before a gathering of Goldman par=
tners, groused about his successor, according to people familiar with the m=
atter. David Solomon, Blankfein said, was spending too much time away from =
his day job, jetting around on Goldman=E2=80=99s private planes and DJing a=
t nightclubs and festivals.=C2=A0
Blankfein wasn=E2=80=99t the only one complaining. Partners faulted Solomon=
, who wasn=E2=80=99t present at the bar, for presiding over a money-losing =
expansion into consumer lending that Goldman is now unwinding. The consumer=
 business, they said, didn=E2=80=99t make the partners money. That stood in=
 contrast with the bank=E2=80=99s other units.
Cracks are forming in a Wall Street institution: the vaunted Goldman Sachs =
partnership.=C2=A0

And one of the conservative older bankers who advised against the DJing=C2=
=A0is actually named:
John Rogers, a Goldman partner since 2000, and the secretary to the bank=E2=
=80=99s board, expressed concerns to Solomon about his DJ side gig, accordi=
ng to people familiar with the matter, saying it wasn=E2=80=99t a good look=
 for the CEO of one of Wall Street=E2=80=99s most formidable firms.
Just an absolutely Shakespearean palace coup brewing here, all these Goldma=
n partners plotting revolt because their CEO is also a DJ.=C2=A0
I am =E2=80=A6=C2=A0partially =E2=80=A6=C2=A0kidding? Actually the disputes=
 seem to be more about money and strategy and, in particular, the power of =
the Goldman partnership:

Since the late 1800s, Goldman partners have weighed in on the firm=E2=80=99=
s direction. They conveyed their opinions to Goldman=E2=80=99s chief=E2=80=
=94for a long time known as the senior partner=E2=80=94and engaged in debat=
e. Partners sometimes overruled the CEO or persuaded him to go along with t=
heir plans.=C2=A0
For a long time, the CEO was viewed as one of many, less a benign dictator =
and more the bank=E2=80=99s public face and standard-bearer. Blankfein ofte=
n behaved like the senior partner, people familiar with the matter said, pr=
eferring persuasion to decree when it came to decision-making.
Things changed when Solomon got the top job in 2018. ...=C2=A0
Solomon, the first CEO who didn=E2=80=99t work at the bank when it was a pr=
ivate partnership, did away with the flat hierarchy that gave partners wide=
 leeway to call their own shots. Longtime partners said they found it harde=
r to communicate with Solomon than Blankfein, who encouraged people to stop=
 by his office for informal chats.

Solomon=E2=80=99s model is that Goldman Sachs is a publicly traded corporat=
ion and he is the chief executive officer of it. That model is factually ac=
curate, but Goldman has spent a long time sort of pretending that it is in =
fact a private partnership, largely for good cultural and risk-management r=
easons, and you can see why the partners would be attached to=C2=A0that=C2=
=A0model.
Meanwhile at Semafor, Liz Hoffman reports:

Less than two years after Goldman Sachs paid nearly $2 billion for a specia=
lty lender, the firm is now unwinding the deal at a significant loss as it =
retreats from its ambitions on Main Street.
