<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Naked short selling</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CNaked short selling is an imaginary p=
roblem,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
1780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjMtMDYtMDgvZG9uLXQtc3F1ZWV6ZS10aGUtc2hvcnRzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MTMyM19NT05FWVN=
UVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMD=
YxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc496ac6d" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">  I said last week</a>, enraging apparently hundreds of very online in=
vestors in a now-private oil company called Next Bridge Hydrocarbons Inc. f=
or reasons that are, I promise, not worth getting into. And so of course ye=
sterday the US Securities and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy0xMDc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe698daf4" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> brought a naked short selling enforcement action</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today c=
harged investment adviser Sabby Management LLC and its managing partner, Ha=
l D. Mintz, with fraud in connection with a long running scheme involving m=
isrepresentations and violations of rules for short selling and order makin=
g, as well as other violative trading, that generated more than $2 million =
in illegal profits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint alleges that, from=
 at least March 2017 through May 2019, Sabby and Mintz repeatedly circumven=
ted trading rules to conduct unlawful trades in the stock of at least 10 pu=
blic companies. Short selling is a legal practice where, generally, a trade=
r borrows a security from a securityholder and sells the security at one pr=
ice, speculating that the trader can buy the security at a lower price in t=
he future before it must be returned to its owner. As alleged in the compla=
int, for example, Sabby and Mintz engaged in illegal =E2=80=9Cnaked short s=
elling=E2=80=9D by intentionally and improperly placing short sales when th=
ey knew or were reckless in not knowing that they had not borrowed or locat=
ed the shares, and then failed to make timely delivery of the shares. Accor=
ding to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, the purpose of Sabby and Mintz=E2=80=
=99s fraudulent scheme was to earn profits they could not have gained throu=
gh legal trading.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/31780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9pbnZlc3Rvci9wdWJz=
L3JlZ3Noby5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3339091e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> basic rule</a> =
is that if you want to sell stock short =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, sell it wit=
hout owning it, to bet on its decline =E2=80=94=C2=A0you have to borrow the=
 stock that you sell from someone who owns it, and generally pay them a fee=
 for the use of their stock.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And before you sell the stock,=C2=A0you need to get a =E2=80=9Clo=
cate,=E2=80=9D meaning that your broker checks and tells you=C2=A0=E2=80=9C=
yeah you can probably borrow enough=C2=A0shares for this short.=E2=80=9D<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You get a locate, you sell the stock, and then you have to delive=
r the stock when the trade settles two days later. So, between the trade an=
d the settlement,=C2=A0the broker who gave you the locate goes out and actu=
ally borrows the stock for you. If you do not borrow the stock in time to s=
ettle the transaction, that is called a =E2=80=9Cfail.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you do not get a locate before the trade, o=
r if you do not manage to borrow the stock before the trade is supposed to =
settle (and the trade fails), that is what is sometimes called a =E2=80=9Cn=
aked short.=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=9CIn a =E2=80=98naked=E2=80=99 short sale, a s=
eller does not borrow or arrange to borrow securities<br />in time to make =
delivery to the buyer within the standard settlement period,=E2=80=9D <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31780057.258413/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMy9jb21wLXByMj=
AyMy0xMDcucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb17db872" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> says yesterday=
=E2=80=99s SEC complaint</a>.) Naked short selling is somewhere between unf=
ortunate (if, say, a market maker does a short sale and can=E2=80=99t find =
borrow in time for normal settlement) and illegal (if a hedge fund=C2=A0sho=
rts a=C2=A0stock without bothering to get a locate).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is out there a conspiracy-theory version=
 of naked short selling.=C2=A0In this version, shadowy hedge funds sell mil=
lions of shares of stock of some good innocent company, without actually bo=
rrowing the stock, and then keep these short positions open forever, drivin=
g the company=E2=80=99s stock down to profit from its failure. This version=
 does not make a ton of sense. For one thing, brokers won=E2=80=99t actuall=
y let you keep naked short positions open forever: If you can=E2=80=99t bor=
row the stock reasonably promptly, they=E2=80=99ll <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm=
5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0Mi4yMDQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0de558cc" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> close out your position by buying back the stock</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also many of the conspiracy-theory versions in=
volve confusion between=C2=A0<em>naked=C2=A0</em>short selling and just=C2=
=A0<em>regular=C2=A0</em>short selling. Conspiracy theorists sometimes poin=
t out that people often <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/31780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMTctMDItMTcvZG9sZS1mb29kLWhhZC10b28tbWFueS1zaGFyZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYx=
MzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXR=
tX3Rlcm09MjMwNjEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
024474e0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  own more than 100% of the outstanding shares</a> of som=
e company, which they take to be proof that there are =E2=80=9Cphantom shar=
es=E2=80=9D created by naked short selling. But <em>any=C2=A0</em>short sel=
ling =E2=80=94=C2=A0including perfectly legal, clothed short selling =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0will have this effect. If there are 100 shares of a company=E2=80=
=99s stock outstanding, and Amy owns all of them, and she=C2=A0lends Ben 20=
 shares to short, and Ben sells those shares to Camille, then Amy owns 100 =
shares and Camille owns 20, for a total of 120 shares; there is simply noth=
ing nefarious or unusual about this. (Sadly we have <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjUvdGhlLWdhbWUtbmV2ZXItc3RvcHM_=
Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYxMzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5=
ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZmI2Zvb3Rub3=
RlLTM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3e8b84c5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  discussed this a lot</=
a>.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More generally, if you just want to bet that a=
 company=E2=80=99s stock will go down, or even=C2=A0<em>drive=C2=A0</em>dow=
n the stock with your own selling activity, you don=E2=80=99t generally nee=
d to=C2=A0<em>naked=C2=A0</em>short. Just regular, legal shorting =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0borrowing stock and selling it =E2=80=94 is a bet against the stock, =
and if you do enough of it it might move the stock. Naked short selling, as=
 a nefarious plot by hedge funds to drive good companies out of business, s=
till seems to me to be a largely imaginary problem.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is, however, a good=C2=A0(illegal! but p=
ossibly lucrative)=C2=A0<em>real</em> use case for naked shorting, albeit s=
ort of a strange and specialized one. It goes like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A publicly traded company is having s=
ome tough times and is looking to raise a bit of money. Ordinary financing =
options like a bond deal or a public stock offering are not available for w=
hatever reason, so the company is looking for weird trades.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You arrange=C2=A0to=C2=A0<em>buy </em>some stock =
from the=C2=A0company, in the future, either at a fixed price or at some fl=
oating price indexed to the market price. So you sign a contract to buy 1 m=
illion shares two weeks from now at $1 per share (a fixed price), or to buy=
 1 million shares two weeks from now at the volume-weighted average price<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0of the stock over next two weeks (a floating price). You are givi=
ng the company money, and you are getting back stock, and because the compa=
ny is a bit desperate you get a pretty good deal.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">The stock is trading at, like, $1.25 today: You are getting=
 a discount, buying at $1, because the company needs the money. (Or if you =
are buying at a floating price, it might be at a discount to the average ma=
rket price.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you could <em>sell=
</em> 1 million shares at $1.25 today, then in two weeks you will buy them =
at $1, and you will make a $250,000 guaranteed profit. Whereas if you wait =
the two weeks, buy the shares at $1, and=C2=A0<em>then=C2=A0</em>sell them,=
 maybe the stock will be below $1 by then and you will lose money. This com=
pany is risky! You want to lock in the profit now. (Similarly, but slightly=
 more complicated, with a floating price: You want to sell the stock over t=
he two-week period so you can <em>get=C2=A0</em>the average price, rather t=
han waiting to <em>buy=C2=A0</em>at that price and then sell at whatever th=
e price is in two weeks.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But, loo=
k:=C2=A0If you have this sort of arrangement with this sort of troubled com=
pany, there is a good chance that=C2=A0it is=C2=A0<em>hard to borrow=C2=A0<=
/em>1 million shares. The company is small, its stock doesn=E2=80=99t trade=
 that much, probably a lot of people have already borrowed it to short it.=
=C2=A0So you have to pay a large borrow fee, or more likely you simply cann=
ot find 1 million shares to borrow at any price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">If you just=C2=A0<em>naked=C2=A0</em>shorted the stock, and =
sort of strung your brokers along for two weeks, you=E2=80=99d be fine: Sel=
l at $1.25 today, buy at $1 in two weeks, and deliver the 1 million shares =
you=C2=A0<em>bought=C2=A0</em>to close out your short position. No harm don=
e!</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is illegal in part because you are unfair=
ly ducking the costs of short selling, but also because it is kind of a sca=
mmy way to do a stock=C2=A0<em>offering: </em>You are basically able to loc=
k in a big profit by selling the stock to the company=E2=80=99s public shar=
eholders before you buy it from the company, and it seems a bit unfair.<a c=
lass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpare=
nt !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked about this idea a few times bef=
ore.=C2=A0We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
31780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjEtMTItMTMvdGhlLXRydW1wLXNwYWMtcGlwZS1pcy1mcmVlLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MT=
MyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0b=
V90ZXJtPTIzMDYxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
c99993f5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  talked</a>, for <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/31780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMDYvdGhlLXRydW1wLXNwYWMtZGlkLWEtcGlwZT9jbXBpZD1C=
QkQwNjEzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHR=
lciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB21de6657" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">  instance</a>, about the PIPE (private investment=
 in public equity) deal done by Digital World Acquisition Corp., the specia=
l purpose acquisition company that is waiting around to try to take Donald =
Trump=E2=80=99s media company public. Roughly speaking, the deal there was =
that the PIPE investors agreed, in December 2021, to buy DWAC stock at $33.=
60 per share whenever the Trump merger closed.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The stock was trading at about $45 at the time. The merger still =
has not closed and probably never will; the stock closed yesterday at $12.7=
9. If you had=C2=A0<em>shorted=C2=A0</em>the stock when you signed the PIPE=
 deal, you=E2=80=99d be hedged: You sell at $45, the deal closes and you bu=
y back at $33.60, or else the deal does not close, the stock falls,=C2=A0an=
d you buy back at, you know, $10. The PIPE deal=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMTMvdGhlLXRydW1wLXNwYWMtcGlwZS1=
pcy1mcmVlLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MTMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haW=
wmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZ=
XlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCc99993f5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"><em>specifically allow=
ed investors to short</em></a>=C2=A0to lock in this profit. But, I wrote:</=
p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are risks to this trade. One=
 risk is that it might be expensive to borrow DWAC stock, it=E2=80=99s a me=
me stock, the price could go up, borrow could be recalled, and you could be=
 forced to cover your short at a loss before the merger closes. If you make=
 it to closing, you=E2=80=99re guaranteed to be able to buy the stock for $=
33.60 for a risk-free profit, but you had better be sure that your stock bo=
rrow is locked up until then. And closing =E2=80=94 which requires writing =
a public disclosure document that satisfies SEC rules =E2=80=94 could be a =
long way away.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If somehow you could be <em>naked=C2=A0</em>sh=
ort for, like, a year and a half or so, those problems would be solved and =
it would be free money. I don=E2=80=99t think you could =E2=80=94=C2=A0I do=
n=E2=80=99t think anyone did this trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you can see how =
naked shorting would be attractive here.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway that=E2=80=99s the sort of trade that S=
abby allegedly did, though on a smaller scale and not in DWAC. (Though Sabb=
y=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/31780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjItMDEtMjAvYS1nb29kLXJlcHV0YXRpb24taXMtZXhwZW5zaXZlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2=
MTMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB67f2a71b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">an investor in the DWAC PIPE</a>.)=C2=A0From <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31780057.258413/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMy9jb21wLXByMjAyMy0=
xMDcucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCb17db872" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> yesterday=E2=80=99s S=
EC complaint</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In April 2018, Defendants, on behalf of the Wa=
rrant Fund, entered into a securities purchase agreement with Issuer 1 thro=
ugh which Defendants acquired preferred securities that could be converted =
into Issuer 1=E2=80=99s common stock at a conversion price of $0.46 per sha=
re. The agreement contained a provision that, on June 25, 2018, the convers=
ion price of the preferred securities would be adjusted to 80% of the volum=
e-weighted average price (=E2=80=9CVWAP=E2=80=9D) of Issuer 1=E2=80=99s com=
mon stock on the preceding trading day, June 22, 2018 (=E2=80=9Cthe reset p=
rovision=E2=80=9D).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The reset provision gave Defendants a financia=
l incentive to push down the price of Issuer 1=E2=80=99s common stock befor=
e June 22, 2018 in order to receive more common stock upon conversion. =E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With two trading days remaining before the res=
et provision took effect, Defendants intentionally began naked short sellin=
g Issuer 1=E2=80=99s common stock, putting downward pressure on Issuer 1=E2=
=80=99s stock price. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Throughout the day, Defendants, on behalf of t=
he Warrant Fund, submitted to executing brokerdealers materially false and =
misleading order instructions for the long sale of 1,126,033 shares=C2=A0of=
 Issuer 1=E2=80=99s common stock that executed at prices between approximat=
ely $0.29 and $0.33 per share.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Defendants knew, or were reckless in not knowi=
ng, that the sale of all but 286 shares should have been marked as short sa=
les because the Warrant Fund did not have a sufficient net long position in=
 the common stock of Issuer 1 at the time Defendants submitted the orders.<=
/p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically they did not get a locate for these =
short sales, and they tricked their brokers into allowing them by marking t=
he sales as =E2=80=9Clong=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9Cshort.=E2=80=9D (A =
=E2=80=9Clong sale=E2=80=9D is selling stock that you own; a =E2=80=9Cshort=
 sale=E2=80=9D is selling stock that you borrow. Later they sold more share=
s marked as short, but =E2=80=9Cfalsely represented to the executing broker=
-dealers that Defendants had obtained locates.=E2=80=9D) This was, in a leg=
al sense, wrong: They did not own the shares they were selling, so these we=
re not long sales. But it was in some broad economic sense right: They owne=
d=C2=A0<em>convertible preferred=C2=A0</em>shares that they could convert i=
nto the shares they were selling; they had economic exposure to the underly=
ing shares, and could get them easily. And they did:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After the close of trading markets on June 22,=
 2018, Defendants calculated the adjusted conversion rate for the Warrant F=
und=E2=80=99s Issuer 1 preferred securities =E2=80=93 based on 80% of VWAP =
on June 22, 2018 =E2=80=93 to be $0.1779 per share, down from the original =
rate of $0.46 per share.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At or around 5:31 PM Eastern Time on June 22, =
2018, Defendants, on behalf of the Warrant Fund, submitted a conversion not=
ice to Issuer 1 to convert $1,797,017 worth of preferred securities into 10=
,101,280 shares of Issuer 1 common stock at a conversion rate of $0.1779 pe=
r share.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so they had enough shares to settle their =
short sales, which they did, on the normal timeline (with no fails).=C2=A0B=
ut the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t like it:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Defendants intended to use these s=
hares to satisfy the delivery obligations for their June 21 and 22, 2018 sa=
les of Issuer 1 common stock and to try to conceal their violative short sa=
les for which they had failed to obtain locates. However, as Defendants kne=
w or were reckless in not knowing all along, the use of these converted sha=
res to cover their sales would not and did not in any way cure their violat=
ive trading. Delivery of those shares did not cure the fact that they had m=
ismarked their trades as long sales when they were not =E2=80=9Cdeemed to o=
wn=E2=80=9D the shares or did not have a net long position in Issuer 1 at t=
he time they submitted the mismarked orders. Similarly, delivery of those s=
hares did not cure their violations of the locate requirements of Regulatio=
n SHO because they had placed short sales without actually having obtained =
a locate, and as Defendants knew or were reckless in not knowing, they coul=
d not use the fact that they held convertible securities that could be exch=
anged for Issuer 1 stock to satisfy the locate requirement.</p></blockquote=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And they did this because it was lucrative:</p=
>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Defendants had converted $1,797=
,017 worth of Issuer 1 preferred securities prior to the adjustment of the =
conversion rate, effective June 25, 2018, the conversion would have yielded=
 only 3,906,560 shares of Issuer 1 common stock. Instead, by tendering the =
convertible securities after Issuer 1=E2=80=99s stock price plummeted by ov=
er 60% and the conversion rate was adjusted downward, Sabby=E2=80=99s conve=
rsion of $1,797,017 worth of preferred securities at the price of $0.1779 p=
er share resulted in approximately 10.1 million shares of common stock.</p>=
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If they had converted at $0.46 and then sold a=
t about $0.19=C2=A0per share (the closing price on June 22), they would hav=
e lost money. (Also, if they converted first and=C2=A0<em>then=C2=A0</em>so=
ld, they would have been entirely at risk =E2=80=94=C2=A0the price could ha=
ve fallen more.=C2=A0Instead they sold at about $0.22 per share first and <=
em>then</em>=C2=A0converted at about $0.18 per share, a much better trade =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0both more profitable=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>less risky =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0though an illegal one.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC goes through another example in which =
Sabby allegedly (naked) shorted a bunch of another company=E2=80=99s stock =
at prices above $1 and=C2=A0<em>then=C2=A0</em>signed a purchase agreement =
with the company to buy 1 million shares at $1, locking in a profit. That i=
s a risky trade, unless you are pretty sure you=E2=80=99re going to be able=
 to buy the stock from the company.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> But if you are, it=E2=80=99s a pretty safe trade: If the stock is at $=
2, and you sell 1 million shares and push down the price to $1.50, then (1)=
 you probably sold at an average price of about $1.75=C2=A0and (2) you can =
go to the company and say =E2=80=9Chey, the stock closed at $1.50, but we n=
eed a discount to the last closing price to make this big purchase, what ab=
out $1?=E2=80=9D and they=E2=80=99ll probably say yes and you=E2=80=99ll ha=
ve locked in a profit of $0.75 per share.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So! I mean: Yes, there is naked short selling,=
 in the world. But notice that what is happening here is not a shadowy caba=
l of hedge funds conspiring to push down the prices of companies=E2=80=99 s=
tocks to ruin them, and heroic companies fighting back to save their shareh=
olders from the scourge of naked short selling. What is happening here is a=
 hedge fund working=C2=A0<em>with the companies=C2=A0</em>to give them fina=
ncing, and (allegedly) using naked short selling to make a risk-free profit=
 on the trade at the expense of the company=E2=80=99s other, regular shareh=
olders.</p>
